snippet.textDisplay: Kenya is a beautiful and strong woman. But even a Tootsie Pop has a soft center. I'm sure that the emotional and physical rejection from her mother has created some very deep and hidden pain buried inside of Kenya, so she falls back on her coping skills. Things like: "I'm fabulous, no matter what you say. I'm all of that AND a bag of chips, etc." These coping mechanisms may have worked well in Kenya's younger years, and on a superficial level -- but a marriage is not a superficial thing. Nor is raising a psychologically healthy little girl. (Unenlightened) Wounded people, wound people. Most of us think that once we get married, our troubles are all over. Hahaha... But in reality, that is when our troubles begin -- especially if we have deeply ingrained issues (abandonment, betrayal, molestation, etc.) that will no longer allow us to sweep them under the rug. From what I had gathered -- Kenya's husband (Mark) was really thrilled to do the "I married my Queen, and we're throwing an event to help humanity" thing. He WANTED the power couple thing. He was elevated and in the zone. And I saw how he kept looking around for his Queen. Kenya, on the other hand, appeared to be unable to rise to his vibratory level and meet his expectations. She was on a lower vibratory frequency, and "chose" to gossip and complain about others -- rather that co-rule beside her King. Queens don't gossip like that, but spoiled princesses, do. After a certain age, a wombman should glide from the position of princess (daddy's girl), into a Queen (King's wife). Did you know that the name: "Queenie" actually means wife? You disrespected yourself (and your husband), Kenya. OWN IT. It's all about choices, isn't it? And the ironic part was that Kenya was gossiping about Marlo, who just so happened to have been there with a couple of young black boys in need of direction from an older and wiser man! Isn't "THAT" what the event was about -- and NOT about Kenya and her petty dramas?! Kenya, we know you're hurt girl, but you aren't the only one suffering. Only a narcissist would think so. Sure, your mother not talking to you makes you feel bad, but you don't have to let that make you "be" bad. What about the children beaten and starved to death by their mothers, or placed in scalding hot water? Or the children placed with CPS, never to be seen or heard from, again. You KNOW it could have been worse, right Kenya? Pretty on the outside, but what about the inside, Tootsie? I only ever see you drop a tear for yourself, and never for another. Sometimes, getting real with self, and with others, is what makes us beautiful and tender, inwardly: A wombman. No man wants a wombman that's always hard. Where are the other dimensions to Kenya? How can you have true intimacy if you don't ever allow feminine vulnerability? Even a man has to occasionally get in touch with his feminine side. But with Kenya, a man might not ever dare to. Leave the Ego (with the capital "E") at the front door, honey. Mark is a King in search his Queen -- and not the petty town gossip. Kenya owes Mark an apology. But not a fake one. Instead, an apology that comes with DEEP self-reflection, feminine wisdom, and humility. Clean it up! But without becoming a doormat. Seek balance in all things. Honestly, Kenya -- If you were to die within the next 24 hours, what do you think that God would have to say to you? You better get right with God, girl. Watch the youtube channel that highlights NDE's (near death experiences): "2028 END." ("Hosea 4:6, Matthew 10:16")
